1
00:00:03,305 --> 00:00:32,298
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:33,511 --> 00:00:41,920
So I'm continuing what we did last time, which is talk about Nibbana.

3
00:00:41,960 --> 00:00:45,503
That's the short and straight of it.

4
00:00:46,704 --> 00:00:56,073
So here I'm just going to go through a discourse which is addressed by the Buddha to a certain monk called Kedvata.

5
00:00:57,915 --> 00:01:01,780
And as we go through it, you'll see what it's all about.

6
00:01:02,451 --> 00:01:12,906
So he says to Kevita, there was a monk in this community of monks, the Sangha, where a thought arose in his awareness.

7
00:01:13,867 --> 00:01:23,700
Where do these four great elements, the earth property, the liquid property, that's that cohesive elasticity,

8
00:01:24,355 --> 00:01:35,007
The fire property, that's heat and cold, of course, and the wind property, that's movement or stillness or stiffness, the earth property being heavy or light.

9
00:01:35,849 --> 00:01:38,132
So where do they cease without remainder?

10
00:01:38,512 --> 00:01:40,134
In other words, where are they annihilated?

11
00:01:42,057 --> 00:01:48,944
Then he attained such a state of concentration that the way leading to the gods appeared in his focused mind.

12
00:01:49,498 --> 00:01:55,206
And so he approached the gods and these seem to be the lowest of them, the retinue of the four great kings.

13
00:01:55,587 --> 00:02:07,986
He said, friends, where do these four great elements, the earth element, liquid, fire and wind element cease without remainder?

14
00:02:09,087 --> 00:02:18,020
When he had said this, they said to him, well, we also don't know where these four great elements cease without remainder.

15
00:02:18,574 --> 00:02:22,580
But there are the four great kings themselves who are higher and more sublime.

16
00:02:23,801 --> 00:02:26,664
So off he goes to try and find these four great kings.

17
00:02:26,746 --> 00:02:36,437
And when he does, they also say, we also don't know where these four great elements come to an end.

18
00:02:37,378 --> 00:02:38,621
Cease without remainder.

19
00:02:39,401 --> 00:02:44,228
So they suggest that he go a little higher to the gods of the 33.

20
00:02:44,967 --> 00:02:56,698
And when they arrive there, they also say, well, we don't know, but Saka, the ruler of the gods, who is higher and more sublime than we will know.

21
00:02:56,737 --> 00:03:10,570
And in this way, they go up and up through the Yama gods and the Suyama gods and the Santusita gods and the Nimmanarati gods and the Sunamita gods.

22
00:03:10,610 --> 00:03:13,894
So they're going higher and higher and they're all saying the same thing.

23
00:03:14,532 --> 00:03:40,707
i don't know what it is but somebody upstairs knows better so you can see this is getting to be a bit of a satire and then finally the paranamita vasavati who was the chief of the paranamita gods said why don't you go and approach the retinue of brahma so when they when he approaches them he said they said of course well

24
00:03:40,756 --> 00:03:44,860
We don't know, but Brahma himself will know.

25
00:03:45,360 --> 00:03:49,365
So Brahma, of course, was the Vedic creator god.

26
00:03:49,925 --> 00:04:09,025
And you can see here that it's beginning to be a bit of a satire on the way the Brahmins would believe or teach about these various gods, but especially the role of Brahma, who was the creator, the starter of all things, you see.

27
00:04:09,460 --> 00:04:18,591
So this particular monk approaches Brahma and he also asks, where do these four great elements cease without remainder?

28
00:04:21,495 --> 00:04:37,915
And he meets this Brahma, he says, actually, just going back a little bit, he says, that a light shines forth and a radiance appears and Brahma will appear.

29
00:04:38,603 --> 00:04:42,129
But for these are the portents of Brahma's appearance.

30
00:04:42,149 --> 00:04:45,076
Light shines forth and a radiance appears.

31
00:04:45,978 --> 00:04:54,074
So Brahma appears and the monk approaches the great Brahma and says, Friend, where do these four great elements cease without remainder?

32
00:04:54,735 --> 00:04:57,422
And the great Brahma replies,

33
00:04:57,740 --> 00:05:14,487
I, monk, am Brahma, the great Brahma, the conqueror, the unconquered, the all-seeing, the all-powerful, the sovereign Lord, maker, creator, chief, appointer, ruler, father of all that has been and shall be.

34
00:05:15,689 --> 00:05:24,843
And the monk says to him, friend, I didn't ask you if you were Brahma, the great Brahma, the conqueror, the unconquered, and so on and so forth.

35
00:05:25,346 --> 00:05:29,834
I asked you, where do the four great elements cease without remainder?

36
00:05:29,853 --> 00:05:33,939
Well, poor old Brahma, he goes off again with his string of attributes.

37
00:05:34,221 --> 00:05:39,668
I am Brahma, you know, the maker, creator, chief, appointer, ruler, and so on.

38
00:05:40,529 --> 00:05:53,430
So again, he asks him, you see, only this time, the great Brahma, taking the monk by the arm and leading him off to the side, said to him, these gods of the retinue of Brahma believe

39
00:05:53,730 --> 00:05:56,696
There is nothing that the great Brahma does not know.

40
00:05:56,735 --> 00:06:00,041
There is nothing the great Brahma does not see.

41
00:06:00,963 --> 00:06:04,069
There is nothing the great Brahma is unaware of.

42
00:06:04,810 --> 00:06:08,276
There is nothing that the great Brahma has not realized.

43
00:06:09,197 --> 00:06:17,291
That is why I did not say in their presence that I too don't know where the four great elements cease without remainder.

44
00:06:17,795 --> 00:06:19,297
So you've acted wrongly.

45
00:06:19,476 --> 00:06:26,367
You've acted incorrectly in bypassing the Blessed One in search of an answer to this question elsewhere.

46
00:06:27,028 --> 00:06:31,495
Go right back to the Blessed One and on arrival, ask him this question.

47
00:06:31,956 --> 00:06:35,180
However he answers it, you should take it to heart.

48
00:06:36,281 --> 00:06:46,637
And then because of his powers, as a man might flex his arm, he appears from the Brahma world before the Buddha.

49
00:06:48,271 --> 00:06:58,286
Okay, so we've been all the way up through all these higher heavens, these sublime places, and he just doesn't have an answer.

50
00:06:58,547 --> 00:07:03,134
Now, when he comes back down, interestingly enough, the Buddha says this to him.

51
00:07:04,615 --> 00:07:14,151
Once, monk, some seafaring merchants took a shore-sighting bird and set sail in their ship.

52
00:07:15,211 --> 00:07:16,995
When they could not see the shore,

53
00:07:17,295 --> 00:07:19,920
they released the shore-sighting bird.

54
00:07:20,442 --> 00:07:27,053
It flew to the east, south, west, north, straight up, and to all the intermediate points of the compass.

55
00:07:28,237 --> 00:07:31,182
If it saw a shore in any direction, it flew there.

56
00:07:31,682 --> 00:07:36,451
If it did not see the shore in any direction, it returned back to the ship.

57
00:07:36,853 --> 00:07:45,663
In the same way, monk, having gone as far as the Brahma world in search of an answer to your question, you have come right back to my presence.

58
00:07:46,184 --> 00:07:58,677
So it sort of suggests that perhaps there were monks in the order, monks and nuns, monastics, who were still, as it were, going for advice to the Brahmins, especially if they were Brahmins themselves.

59
00:07:59,338 --> 00:08:04,684
I don't know what it actually means, but it's an odd thing to admonish this poor monk.

60
00:08:05,709 --> 00:08:16,740
So anyway, what he says to this monk, he says, your question should not be phrased in this way.

61
00:08:17,259 --> 00:08:28,511
It should be, where do these four great elements, the earth element, liquid element, fire element and wind element cease without remainder?

62
00:08:28,651 --> 00:08:30,752
Instead, it should be phrased like this.

63
00:08:31,754 --> 00:08:34,535
Where do earth, water, fire and air

64
00:08:35,191 --> 00:09:04,152
find no footing where are long and short small and great fair and foul where are name and form body and mind brought to an end and the answer is this okay consciousness that is signless non-manifestive limitless without boundary and all illuminating in all directions full of light

65
00:09:05,346 --> 00:09:09,592
There water, earth, fire and wind find no footing.

66
00:09:10,434 --> 00:09:15,162
There long and short, small and large, pleasant and unpleasant.

67
00:09:15,361 --> 00:09:20,370
There name and form, body and mind have all been brought to an end.

68
00:09:21,211 --> 00:09:27,220
With the cessation of consciousness, all is brought to an end.

69
00:09:27,740 --> 00:09:30,644
Okay, so now we have a problem.

70
00:09:31,890 --> 00:09:44,527
So the Buddha is a little bit like really any person who suddenly sees something which is beyond the culture, which is something which is new to the culture.

71
00:09:44,947 --> 00:09:47,149
And they're always scrabbling for new words.

72
00:09:47,529 --> 00:09:56,802
An obvious example would be Freud, who had to come up with id, ego and superego to get across his model of the human mind.

73
00:09:58,451 --> 00:10:26,788
so here he's using consciousness in two different ways okay so the first consciousness is the one that is going to cease is going to come to an end so this is the consciousness that the buddha describes by sense bases so there's eye consciousness there's ear consciousness nose consciousness mind heart consciousness okay so

74
00:10:27,510 --> 00:10:31,462
This consciousness belongs to the five aggregates.

75
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:53,880
which are the body or our physicality, all our feelings driven by both the body and emotions, all our perceptions and the sankaras, these habits of thought, habits of actions, which we remember create through an act of will, and this consciousness.

76
00:10:54,280 --> 00:11:00,787
So here, this consciousness is like a screen upon which this information arises.

77
00:11:01,488 --> 00:11:01,888
Okay?

78
00:11:02,677 --> 00:11:05,442
That's the consciousness which disappears.

79
00:11:05,863 --> 00:11:10,730
That's the consciousness which can experience these four great elements.

80
00:11:11,951 --> 00:11:18,662
And he goes as far as to say that even the mind and the body also are brought to an end.

81
00:11:18,822 --> 00:11:20,565
But this is not a final end.

82
00:11:21,046 --> 00:11:23,470
It's where they find no footing.

83
00:11:24,912 --> 00:11:30,980
And then he describes this experience, right, which has to be the experience of nibbana.

84
00:11:31,331 --> 00:11:38,240
He says there's a consciousness, so there's a knowing, which is non-manifested.

85
00:11:38,282 --> 00:11:40,985
The word that is nidassanai, cannot be seen.

86
00:11:41,986 --> 00:11:43,368
So what cannot be seen?

87
00:11:43,489 --> 00:11:44,470
What cannot be felt?

88
00:11:44,570 --> 00:11:46,513
It stands for all the sense bases.

89
00:11:47,533 --> 00:11:48,676
And it is limitless.

90
00:11:48,735 --> 00:11:50,197
It doesn't have a boundary.

91
00:11:50,839 --> 00:11:52,780
It's not dependent on anything.

92
00:11:53,702 --> 00:11:54,724
And interestingly,

93
00:11:55,042 --> 00:12:01,817
It is all illuminating, or in another translation, in all directions full of light.

94
00:12:03,179 --> 00:12:09,253
And it is here that the earth, the fire, the wind and water elements find no footing.

95
00:12:16,826 --> 00:12:26,996
So what we have here is, again, a restatement that there is a mundane experience that we have through this form of body and mind.

96
00:12:27,577 --> 00:12:31,961
And there is something which sits within it, but beyond it.

97
00:12:32,562 --> 00:12:42,913
And when we experience what is beyond in its purity, then what is mundane, the body and mind, do not appear.

98
00:12:44,414 --> 00:12:46,277
And that really is

99
00:12:46,611 --> 00:12:50,576
one of the most profound experiences of not-self.

100
00:12:51,479 --> 00:13:00,090
Because everything that we experience, we tend to associate with either by way of identity or possession.

101
00:13:00,571 --> 00:13:07,639
But here, everything's gone, and yet there remains this luminous consciousness.

102
00:13:13,268 --> 00:13:14,830
And just as a reminder,

103
00:13:15,822 --> 00:13:27,261
Going back to the early quotes of last month, here he says there's a dimension where there's no earth, no water, no fire, no wind.

104
00:13:27,282 --> 00:13:32,731
So he's saying the same thing here, but he's not actually telling us what it is.

105
00:13:32,812 --> 00:13:34,455
He's telling us what's not there.

106
00:13:34,789 --> 00:13:42,438
He says no dimension of infinite space, infinite consciousness, nothingness, neither perception nor non-perception.

107
00:13:42,458 --> 00:13:47,745
So there's none of those higher states of mind that we refer to as the jhana, the absorptions.

108
00:13:48,546 --> 00:13:50,388
There's not this world or another world.

109
00:13:50,408 --> 00:13:51,690
There's no moon, no sun.

110
00:13:52,831 --> 00:13:57,076
I say there's no coming or going, remaining or passing away or reappearing.

111
00:13:57,196 --> 00:14:01,640
There's absolutely nothing there which is either phenomenal or physical.

112
00:14:04,523 --> 00:14:08,427
And then we have this other quote, which again tells us what's not there.

113
00:14:09,168 --> 00:14:11,110
There is that which is unborn.

114
00:14:11,150 --> 00:14:13,774
This is how it's translated, unborn.

115
00:14:14,635 --> 00:14:22,725
It's almost a direct translation, unborn, undying, uncreated, uncompounded, which means it's unconditioned.

116
00:14:23,907 --> 00:14:27,451
So there is something which was never born.

117
00:14:28,013 --> 00:14:30,174
It's never died.

118
00:14:30,195 --> 00:14:33,078
It was never created, doesn't develop.

119
00:14:33,447 --> 00:14:58,965
and is not bound by any conditions so we've had these statements now both of the negative what is not in Nibbāna but also this very positive statement about an experience that is Nibbānic and this is only quoted twice within the whole of the scriptures

120
00:14:59,705 --> 00:15:24,361
and it doesn't it doesn't appear in the udana disc in the udana collection which are a collection of his inspired verses so there's some filtering going on and just as a as an aside in the mahayana when buddhism so we say developed into the mahayana there was a school the yogachara school

121
00:15:24,746 --> 00:15:38,907
that actually has a transcendent, that's what they call it, a transcendent Abhidhamma, and it's based upon this particular phrase, this particular verse that we've just been reading.

122
00:15:41,230 --> 00:15:53,707
So this does not complete the mystery of Nibbana, unfortunately, and there's more to be said, and I'll find some time in order to talk about it.

123
00:15:54,464 --> 00:16:10,909
So, I can only hope these words have been of self-assistance, that they have not caused confusion, and that by your careful investigation through your practice of Vipassana, you will attain this particular experience.

124
00:16:11,831 --> 00:16:13,754
Sadhu, sadhu, sadhu.

